      <hedline>
        <hl1>Blood Donor Criteria</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>American Red Cross senior medical officer Rebecca Haley letter responds to June 18 letter that 'inappropriately' accused Red Cross of bigotry for not accepting blood donations from homosexuals (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 18 letter inappropriately accuses the Red Cross of bigotry for not accepting blood from gay men.</p>
        <p>American Red Cross Blood Services provides the safest possible blood for people in need of transfusions. We defer donors according to rules set forth by the Food and Drug Administration that are intended to exclude high-risk individuals from the blood supply.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 18 letter inappropriately accuses the Red Cross of bigotry for not accepting blood from gay men.</p>
        <p>American Red Cross Blood Services provides the safest possible blood for people in need of transfusions. We defer donors according to rules set forth by the Food and Drug Administration that are intended to exclude high-risk individuals from the blood supply.</p>
        <p>These rules are based on epidemiological information from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention collected in the United States, not on opinions about anyone's choice of lifestyle. These criteria have kept blood transfusion extraordinarily safe from disease transmission.</p>
        <p>The Red Cross encourages blood donation from individuals who qualify.</p>
        <p>REBECCA HALEY, M.D.  Senior Medical Officer  American Red Cross  Arlington, Va., June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
